04820nam a22007575i 9781978801394DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020004920  a97819788013947 a10.36019/97819788013942doi  a(DE-B1597)590725  a(OCoLC)1266228366  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN1995.9.B69bV64 2021 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.4365792231 aVogan, Travis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Boxing Film :bA Cultural and Transmedia History /cTravis Vogan. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (214 p.) :b7 b-w images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScreening Sports00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tThe Boxing Film -- tIntroduction: -- t1 The Boxing Film through the Golden Age of Sports Media -- t2 St. Joe Louis, Surrounded by Films -- t3 TV Fighting and Fighting TV in the 1950s -- t4 Muhammad Ali, The Super Fight, and Closed-Circuit Exhibition -- t5 The 1970s, Rocky, and the Shadow of Ali -- t6 HBO Sports: -- t7 Protecting Boxing with the Boxing Film -- tConclusion: -- tFilmography -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs one of popular culture’s most popular arenas, sports are often the subject of cinematic storytelling. But boxing films are special. There are more movies about boxing, by a healthy margin, than any other sport, and boxing accompanied and aided the medium’s late nineteenth-century emergence as a popular mass entertainment. Many of cinema’s most celebrated directors—from Oscar Micheaux to Martin Scorsese—made boxing films. And while the production of other types of sports movies generally corresponds with the current popularity of their subject, boxing films continue to be made regularly even after the sport has wilted from its once-prominent position in the sports hierarchy of the United States. From Edison’s Leonard-Cushing Fight to The Joe Louis Story, Rocky, and beyond, this book explores why boxing has so consistently fascinated cinema and popular media culture by tracing how boxing movies inform the sport’s meanings and uses from the late nineteenth century to the early twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aBoxing filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  aSports, Storytelling, Boxing, Film, Oscar Micheaux, Martin Scorsese, Production, 19th Century, 21st Century, Cinema, Media Culture, Mass Entertainment, HBO Sports, TV Fighting, Rocky, Sports Media, Muhammad Ali, Athleticism, Culture, Fights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2021z9783110753790oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishz978311075403208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073913840uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197880139440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978801394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978801394/original  a978-3-11-073913-8  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075403-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE 